li.p:
Any solution curve that starts with P(0) \gt 3 will decrease to
P(t) = 3 as t \to \infty;
any curve that starts with
1 \lt P(0) \lt 3 will increase to P(t) = 3;
any curve that starts with
0 \lt P(0) \lt 1 will decrease to P(t) = 0.

P = 0,
P = 1, and P = 3. P = 1 is unstable;
P = 0 and P = 3 are stable.

If P(0) \gt 1, the population's value will tend to
P(t) = 3 as t \to \infty;
if P(0) \lt 1,
the population's value will tend to P(t) = 0.
Thus, the population will stabilize either way,
but either at the value P = 3 or at a level that corresponds to the population going extinct.


